						               													<description>&amp;#229;&amp;#167;&amp;#171;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#168;&amp;#233;&amp;#173;&amp;#148;&amp;#230;&amp;#179;&amp;#149;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#174;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#191;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#164;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#171;&amp;#227;&amp;#128;&amp;#156;&amp;#229;&amp;#189;&amp;#188;&amp;#229;&amp;#165;&amp;#179;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#175;&amp;#230;&amp;#132;&amp;#143;&amp;#229;&amp;#164;&amp;#150;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#168;&amp;#233;&amp;#135;&amp;#141;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#139;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#163;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#159;&amp;#227;&amp;#128;&amp;#156; (Hime to mah&amp;#197;&amp;#141; no tairu &amp;#227;&amp;#128;&amp;#156; kanojo wa igaito omokatta &amp;#227;&amp;#128;&amp;#156;) (The Princess and Magic tile) is a Japanese tile placement game. A witch has kidnapped a princess and locked her in a pavillion, bound by magic. The players must complete magic spells to get into the pavillion and rescue her. The full title is &amp;quot;The Princess and Magic Tiles - She Turns Out to Be Amazingly Heavy -&amp;quot;. In the game, as you carry the Princess away to safety, she grows heavier and heavier, cursed by the witch.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;During the game, players place tiles in front of themselves to build a tableau. Players are trying to build certain patterns to match spell cards, open to any player. A pattern works either by have the same symbols on the tile match up, or by having the same background on the tiles match. So a diagonal line of purple stars might fit one spell card, whilst the same tableau also has a crossway pattern with a gold background. Building combos like this helps the player advance quickly.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Once a player reaches the Princess, they carry her away. The player puts the princess token on top of their piece. But the Princess is cursed and weighs too much, slower the player down. In this way, the other players can catch up and carry her away.&amp;#10;